1685
02:09:54.860 --> 02:09:57.070
You have till 6:00
before they change the locks.

1686
02:09:57.240 --> 02:09:58.990
No, I don't need to go over there.

1687
02:09:59.580 --> 02:10:01.490
Do you not want those never-worn shoes?

1688
02:10:01.660 --> 02:10:04.040
Oh, God, I completely forgot.

1689
02:10:04.210 --> 02:10:07.830
If you don't, you can send them to me
and I'll squeeze my feet into them.

1690
02:10:08.000 --> 02:10:09.880
But it's already 5:00.

1691
02:10:10.040 --> 02:10:13.550
Hello? They are never-been-worn'
$400 shoes.

1692
02:10:13.710 --> 02:10:18.590
Actually 525.
Yeah, okay. All right, thanks. Bye.

1693
02:10:19.430 --> 02:10:21.470
Taxi!

1694
02:10:30.940 --> 02:10:34.440
The light in our prewar apartment...

1695
02:10:34.610 --> 02:10:37.900
...looked completely different postwar.

1696
02:10:58.510 --> 02:11:03.220
I was gonna get these to you.
I didn't want it to be a total loss.

1697
02:11:03.510 --> 02:11:07.390
It wasn't logic, it was love.

1698
02:11:28.500 --> 02:11:31.500
Why did we ever decide to get married?

1699
02:11:33.670 --> 02:11:39.170
I guess we were afraid
it would mean something if we didn't.

1700
02:11:43.390 --> 02:11:49.850
I'm sorry to have done that to you.

1701
02:11:53.860 --> 02:11:55.940
You know the funny part?

1702
02:11:57.990 --> 02:12:00.200
Is there a funny part?

1703
02:12:00.360 --> 02:12:04.660
We were perfectly happy before
we decided to live happily ever after.

1704
02:12:05.120 --> 02:12:06.990
Guess the joke's on us.

1705
02:12:16.050 --> 02:12:19.880
- It's a good closet.
- Thanks.

1706
02:12:23.180 --> 02:12:25.550
It's comfortable.

1707
02:12:25.890 --> 02:12:29.220
Is this what you had in mind
when you installed the carpet?

1708
02:12:30.270 --> 02:12:33.270
I'd like to think I was that smooth.

1709
02:12:40.700 --> 02:12:44.530
We better get up
before the new owners bust in on us.

1710
02:12:53.580 --> 02:12:57.340
And the way we decided to get married...

1711
02:12:57.500 --> 02:12:59.420
...it was all business.

1712
02:12:59.590 --> 02:13:01.760
No romance.

1713
02:13:04.260 --> 02:13:09.350
That's not the way
you propose to someone.

1714
02:13:10.770 --> 02:13:12.770
This is.

1715
02:13:16.270 --> 02:13:18.360
Carrie Bradshaw...

1716
02:13:19.070 --> 02:13:20.440
...love of my life...

1717
02:13:23.320 --> 02:13:25.360
...will you marry me?

1718
02:13:30.240 --> 02:13:32.580
See, this is why there's a diamond.

1719
02:13:32.750 --> 02:13:34.870
You need to do something
to close the deal.

1720
02:13:59.440 --> 02:14:00.650
And forsaking all others...

1721
02:14:00.820 --> 02:14:04.690
And in the end, Carrie Bradshaw
married John James Preston...

1722
02:14:04.860 --> 02:14:06.530
...in a label-less dress.
- I do.

1723
02:14:06.990 --> 02:14:09.660
Then by the power vested in me
by the state of New York...

1724
02:14:09.830 --> 02:14:14.410
...I now pronounce you husband and wife.
You may kiss the bride.

1725
02:14:25.010 --> 02:14:27.010
Ever thine. Ever mine.

1726
02:14:27.800 --> 02:14:30.470
Ever ours.

1727
02:14:32.890 --> 02:14:35.230
So you're okay that it was just us?

1728
02:14:35.390 --> 02:14:39.980
It was perfect. You and me, like I said.

1729
02:14:40.150 --> 02:14:43.400
Still, it would have been nice
if you had the girls here.

1730
02:14:45.070 --> 02:14:47.490
Which is why I called them.

1731
02:14:51.780 --> 02:14:54.490
- Hi, Carrie!
- Mazel tov!

1732
02:14:57.710 --> 02:15:00.790
- Ham and eggs. Ham and eggs for you, sir.
- Yup, that's me.

1733
02:15:00.960 --> 02:15:03.630
It wasn't a fancy, designer reception either.

1734
02:15:04.170 --> 02:15:06.300
Just food and friends.

1735
02:15:08.510 --> 02:15:10.390
Butter, ma'am?

1736
02:15:12.640 --> 02:15:14.350
How's the marriage going?

1737
02:15:34.540 --> 02:15:39.710
"And as I put the wedding gown away'
I couldn't help but wonder:

1738
02:15:39.870 --> 02:15:44.090
'Why is it that we're willing
to write our own vows...

1739
02:15:44.250 --> 02:15:47.760
...but not our own rules?"'

1740
02:15:47.970 --> 02:15:50.470
And that's just a little something
I'm working on.

1741
02:15:52.930 --> 02:15:54.680
Thank you.

1742
02:15:56.350 --> 02:15:58.020
Oh, my God.

1743
02:16:00.440 --> 02:16:03.100
Maybe some labels
are best left in the closet.

1744
02:16:03.270 --> 02:16:04.770
Maybe when we label people:

1745
02:16:04.940 --> 02:16:09.190
"Bride," "groom," "husband,"
"wife," "married," "single"...

1746
02:16:09.360 --> 02:16:12.860
...we forget to look past the label
to the person.

1747
02:16:14.070 --> 02:16:17.120
- This is delicious.
- Why did we ever stop drinking these?

1748
02:16:17.290 --> 02:16:20.910
- Because everyone else started.
- Well, that one's an oldie but goodie.

1749
02:16:21.080 --> 02:16:23.880
And speaking of an oldie but goodie...

1750
02:16:26.800 --> 02:16:28.920
- Happy birthday.
- Happy birthday.

1751
02:16:29.880 --> 02:16:31.930
Wait, wait, wait. A toast.

1752
02:16:32.090 --> 02:16:33.640
To Samantha.

1753
02:16:33.800 --> 02:16:36.550
Fifty and fabulous.

1754
02:16:42.650 --> 02:16:44.480
To us...

1755
02:16:46.230 --> 02:16:47.320
...and the next 50.

1756
02:16:47.480 --> 02:16:49.820
To the next 50.

1757
02:16:51.900 --> 02:16:56.280
And there, in the same city
where they met as girls...

1758
02:16:56.450 --> 02:17:00.790
...four New York women
entered the next phase of their lives...

1759
02:17:00.960 --> 02:17:04.580
...dressed head to toe in love.

1760
02:17:05.210 --> 02:17:07.420
And that's the one label...

1761
02:17:07.590 --> 02:17:10.800
...that never goes out of style.

